ML MLS Session Deck: Topic-wise Description

1. Types of Machine Learning
- Machine Learning is categorized into Regression, Classification, and Clustering.
  - Regression: Used for predicting continuous numerical values (e.g., sales, prices). Data is structured with a numerical target variable.
  - Classification: Used for assigning items to categories (e.g., spam detection). Data is structured with a categorical target variable.
  - Clustering: Used for grouping similar data without predefined labels (e.g., customer types). Data can be structured or unstructured, and there is no target variable.

2. Machine Learning Quiz (Regression)
- Linear regression models predict sales based on advertising spend. The error in predictions is measured by the difference between actual and predicted values (residuals).

3. Prediction Errors in Linear Regression
- Error (residual) is the difference between the actual value and the predicted value. Smaller errors indicate better model fit.

4. Machine Learning Quiz (Regression Metrics)
- To evaluate model performance with more weight on larger errors, metrics like Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) and Mean Squared Error (MSE) are used. RMSE is sensitive to outliers due to the square function.

5. Evaluation Metrics: Regression
- Root Mean Square Error (RMSE): Measures accuracy, same unit as dependent variable, sensitive to outliers, lower is better.
- Mean Absolute Error (MAE): Simplest metric, same unit, not sensitive to outliers, lower is better.
- Mean Squared Error (MSE): Penalizes larger errors, sensitive to outliers, lower is better.
- Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE): Shows average error as a percentage, easy to interpret, can be unstable if actual values are near zero, lower is better.

6. Machine Learning Quiz (Classification Metrics)
- In medical diagnosis, recall is the most important metric when the priority is to identify as many diseased patients as possible, even if some healthy patients are wrongly flagged.

7. Evaluation Metrics: Classification
- Classification problems (e.g., disease detection) have four possible outcomes:
  - True Positive: Diseased patient correctly identified
  - True Negative: Healthy patient correctly identified
  - False Positive: Healthy patient wrongly flagged as diseased
  - False Negative: Diseased patient wrongly flagged as healthy
- Metrics like precision, recall, accuracy, and F1 score are used to evaluate classification models. Recall is crucial when missing a positive case is costly (e.g., disease detection).

